Proposed Analysis

I want to look at binding pattern differences between the WT and mutant Runx2. For this I have four questions that I want to answer: 1. What regulatory elements are bound by the WT and the mutant? 2. Runx2 WT and mutant binding to TSS regions? 3. How is the enrichment of the protein binding affected across the chromosomes for WT and mutant? 4. Functional enrichment analysis for WT and mutant?

I will be using the ChIP-seq specific R Bioconductor packages to do my ChIP-seq analysis.

ChIP Peaks Plot of WT and Mutant Runx2

  • This plot is used to know the peak locations over the whole genome.
  • Covplot function calculates the coverage of peak regions over chromosomes
covplot(wt, weightCol="V5", title = "Runx2 WT ChIP Peaks over Chromosomes")

covplot(mutant, weightCol="V5", title = "Runx2 Mutant ChIP Peaks over Chromosomes")

## Overlap of peaks between the WT and Mutant Runx2 >- To Test the overlaps of all the peaks. >- From the testing result, we can check the association between WT and Mutant Runx2. >- The vennDiagram shows the numbers of overlapping peak for these TFs.

olpeaks <- findOverlapsOfPeaks(wt, mutant)
## duplicated or NA names found. 
##                 Rename all the names by numbers.
## duplicated or NA names found. 
##                 Rename all the names by numbers.
makeVennDiagram(olpeaks,
                fill=c("#009E73", "#F0E442"), # circle fill color
                col=c("#D55E00", "#0072B2"), #circle border color
                cat.col=c("#D55E00", "#0072B2"))
## Missing totalTest! totalTest is required for HyperG test. 
## If totalTest is missing, pvalue will be calculated by estimating 
## the total binding sites of encoding region of human.
## totalTest = humanGenomeSize * (2%(codingDNA) + 
##              1%(regulationRegion)) / ( 2 * averagePeakWidth )
##           = 3.3e+9 * 0.03 / ( 2 * averagePeakWidth)
##           = 5e+7 /averagePeakWidth

Heatmap of ChIP binding of Runx2 WT and mutant to TSS regions

promoter <- getPromoters(TxDb = txdb, upstream=1000, downstream=1000)
tagMatrix <- lapply(peaklist, getTagMatrix, windows=promoter)
tagHeatmap(tagMatrix, xlim=c(-1000, 1000), color="red")

## Average profile of ChIP peaks binding of Runx2 WT and mutant to TSS regions >- Compare the average binding profile of WT and Mutant Runx2.

plotAvgProf(tagMatrix, xlim=c(-1000, 1000), facet="row")

## ChIP peak genomic annotation comparison between Runx2 WT and mutant. >- This is done to annotate the location of a given peak in terms of genomic features. >- annotatePeak function assigns peaks to genomic annotation in “annotation”

peakAnnoList <- lapply(peaklist, annotatePeak, TxDb=txdb,
                       tssRegion=c(-1000, 1000), verbose=FALSE)
plotAnnoBar(peakAnnoList)

## Visualize distribution of Runx2 WT and mutant binding loci relative to TSS >- R function plotDistToTSS can be used to compare distance to TSS profiles among ChIPseq data. >- plotDistToTSS can calculate the percentage of binding sites upstream and downstream from the TSS of the nearest genes, and visualize the distribution.

plotDistToTSS(peakAnnoList)

## Functional Profile Comparison of Runx2 WT and mutant >- The clusterProfiler package provides compareCluster function for comparing biological themes among gene clusters, and can be easily adopted to compare different ChIP peak experiments.

genes_list = lapply(peakAnnoList, function(i) as.data.frame(i)$geneId)
names(genes_list) = sub("_", "\n", names(genes_list))

comp_path <- compareCluster(geneClusters = genes_list, fun = "enrichPathway", pvalueCutoff  = 0.05, pAdjustMethod = "BH")                 
dotplot(comp_path, showCategory = 12, title = "Pathway Enrichment Analysis")

## Overlap of annotated genes between Runx2 WT and mutant >- vennplot function can be used to visualize the overlap of the nearest genes stored in peakAnnoList.

vennplot(genes_list)
